{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01D66ZiASYXuia4k8RdznsEV","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→Feature: Run Queries\n     2→  Canonical run status, durable history, and runtime-log separation.\n     3→\n     4→  # SC-RUN-001\n     5→  Scenario: Run status reports \"not started\" for a new project\n     6→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" selected as active\n     7→    And project \"alpha\" has no active run\n     8→    When the user runs \"run status\"\n     9→    Then the output includes \"not started\"\n    10→    And the status is read from canonical run state, not inferred from artifacts\n    11→\n    12→  # SC-RUN-002\n    13→  Scenario: Run status reports active run with stage cursor\n    14→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" that has an active run\n    15→    When the user runs \"run status\"\n    16→    Then the output includes run status, current stage, cycle, and completion round\n    17→    And the status is derived from canonical run.json, not artifact scans\n    18→\n    19→  # SC-RUN-003\n    20→  Scenario: Run history shows durable history only\n    21→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" selected as active\n    22→    And project \"alpha\" has journal events and payload/artifact records\n    23→    When the user runs \"run history\"\n    24→    Then the output includes journal events in canonical order\n    25→    And the output includes payload and artifact records\n    26→    And the output does not include runtime logs\n    27→\n    28→  # SC-RUN-004\n    29→  Scenario: Run history never includes runtime logs\n    30→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" that has runtime logs\n    31→    When the user runs \"run history\"\n    32→    Then the output does not contain any runtime log entries\n    33→\n    34→  # SC-RUN-005\n    35→  Scenario: Run tail shows durable history only by default\n    36→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" selected as active\n    37→    When the user runs \"run tail\"\n    38→    Then the output includes durable history (journal events)\n    39→    And the output does not include a runtime logs section\n    40→\n    41→  # SC-RUN-006\n    42→  Scenario: Run tail --logs appends runtime logs after durable history\n    43→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" selected as active\n    44→    And project \"alpha\" has runtime logs\n    45→    When the user runs \"run tail --logs\"\n    46→    Then the output includes durable history section\n    47→    And the output includes a runtime logs section after the durable section\n    48→    And the durable history portion is unchanged compared to \"run tail\" without --logs\n    49→\n    50→  # SC-RUN-007\n    51→  Scenario: Corrupt canonical files fail fast with file-specific errors\n    52→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\"\n    53→    And \"run.json\" for project \"alpha\" contains invalid JSON\n    54→    When the user runs \"run status\"\n    55→    Then the command fails with error referencing \"run.json\"\n    56→    And the command does not fall back to Markdown or directory scans\n    57→\n    58→  # SC-RUN-008\n    59→  Scenario: Corrupt journal fails fast\n    60→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\"\n    61→    And \"journal.ndjson\" for project \"alpha\" contains a sequence gap\n    62→    When the user runs \"run history\"\n    63→    Then the command fails with error containing \"journal sequence\"\n    64→\n    65→  # SC-RUN-009\n    66→  Scenario: Orphaned artifact record fails consistency check\n    67→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\"\n    68→    And project \"alpha\" has an artifact referencing a non-existent payload\n    69→    When the user runs \"run history\"\n    70→    Then the command fails with error containing \"does not exist\"\n    71→\n    72→  # SC-RUN-010\n    73→  Scenario: Runtime log write failures do not affect durable history\n    74→    Given runtime log writes are failing\n    75→    When durable history is queried via \"run history\"\n    76→    Then durable history records are returned intact\n    77→    And no durable history records are fabricated, removed, or reordered\n    78→\n    79→  # SC-RUN-011\n    80→  Scenario: Missing run.json fails fast\n    81→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\"\n    82→    And \"run.json\" for project \"alpha\" has been deleted\n    83→    When the user runs \"run status\"\n    84→    Then the command fails with error referencing \"run.json\" and \"missing\"\n    85→\n    86→  # SC-RUN-012\n    87→  Scenario: Missing journal.ndjson fails fast\n    88→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\"\n    89→    And \"journal.ndjson\" for project \"alpha\" has been deleted\n    90→    When the user runs \"run history\"\n    91→    Then the command fails with error referencing \"journal.ndjson\" and \"missing\"\n    92→\n    93→  # SC-RUN-013\n    94→  Scenario: Orphaned payload record fails consistency check\n    95→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\"\n    96→    And project \"alpha\" has a payload with no matching artifact\n    97→    When the user runs \"run history\"\n    98→    Then the command fails with error containing \"no matching artifact\"\n    99→\n   100→  # SC-RUN-014\n   101→  Scenario: Run tail includes payload and artifact records in durable section\n   102→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" that has payload and artifact records\n   103→    When the user runs \"run tail\"\n   104→    Then the durable section includes payload and artifact records\n   105→    And the output matches what \"run history\" would show for the same data\n   106→\n   107→  # SC-RUN-015\n   108→  Scenario: Run status reports terminal completed state without active run\n   109→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" selected as active\n   110→    And \"run.json\" for project \"alpha\" contains status \"completed\" with active_run null\n   111→    When the user runs \"run status\"\n   112→    Then the output includes \"completed\"\n   113→    And the output does not include \"not started\"\n   114→\n   115→  # SC-RUN-016\n   116→  Scenario: Run status reports terminal failed state without active run\n   117→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" selected as active\n   118→    And \"run.json\" for project \"alpha\" contains status \"failed\" with active_run null\n   119→    When the user runs \"run status\"\n   120→    Then the output includes \"failed\"\n   121→    And the output does not include \"not started\"\n   122→\n   123→  # SC-RUN-017\n   124→  Scenario: Semantically inconsistent run.json fails fast\n   125→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" selected as active\n   126→    And \"run.json\" for project \"alpha\" contains status \"running\" with active_run null\n   127→    When the user runs \"run status\"\n   128→    Then the command fails with error referencing \"run.json\" and \"inconsistent\"\n   129→\n   130→  # SC-RUN-018\n   131→  Scenario: Project delete fails for semantically inconsistent paused snapshot\n   132→    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\"\n   133→    And \"run.json\" for project \"alpha\" contains status \"paused\" with active_run null\n   134→    When the user runs \"project delete alpha\"\n   135→    Then the command fails with error referencing \"run.json\" and \"inconsistent\"\n   136→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5eb81d8b-9dcb-415b-a8cb-cb111e8f40b3","uuid":"e961991e-81a6-4020-bfa8-1790ad3da8e6","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/run_queries.feature","content":"Feature: Run Queries\n  Canonical run status, durable history, and runtime-log separation.\n\n  # SC-RUN-001\n  Scenario: Run status reports \"not started\" for a new project\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" selected as active\n    And project \"alpha\" has no active run\n    When the user runs \"run status\"\n    Then the output includes \"not started\"\n    And the status is read from canonical run state, not inferred from artifacts\n\n  # SC-RUN-002\n  Scenario: Run status reports active run with stage cursor\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" that has an active run\n    When the user runs \"run status\"\n    Then the output includes run status, current stage, cycle, and completion round\n    And the status is derived from canonical run.json, not artifact scans\n\n  # SC-RUN-003\n  Scenario: Run history shows durable history only\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" selected as active\n    And project \"alpha\" has journal events and payload/artifact records\n    When the user runs \"run history\"\n    Then the output includes journal events in canonical order\n    And the output includes payload and artifact records\n    And the output does not include runtime logs\n\n  # SC-RUN-004\n  Scenario: Run history never includes runtime logs\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" that has runtime logs\n    When the user runs \"run history\"\n    Then the output does not contain any runtime log entries\n\n  # SC-RUN-005\n  Scenario: Run tail shows durable history only by default\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" selected as active\n    When the user runs \"run tail\"\n    Then the output includes durable history (journal events)\n    And the output does not include a runtime logs section\n\n  # SC-RUN-006\n  Scenario: Run tail --logs appends runtime logs after durable history\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" selected as active\n    And project \"alpha\" has runtime logs\n    When the user runs \"run tail --logs\"\n    Then the output includes durable history section\n    And the output includes a runtime logs section after the durable section\n    And the durable history portion is unchanged compared to \"run tail\" without --logs\n\n  # SC-RUN-007\n  Scenario: Corrupt canonical files fail fast with file-specific errors\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\"\n    And \"run.json\" for project \"alpha\" contains invalid JSON\n    When the user runs \"run status\"\n    Then the command fails with error referencing \"run.json\"\n    And the command does not fall back to Markdown or directory scans\n\n  # SC-RUN-008\n  Scenario: Corrupt journal fails fast\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\"\n    And \"journal.ndjson\" for project \"alpha\" contains a sequence gap\n    When the user runs \"run history\"\n    Then the command fails with error containing \"journal sequence\"\n\n  # SC-RUN-009\n  Scenario: Orphaned artifact record fails consistency check\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\"\n    And project \"alpha\" has an artifact referencing a non-existent payload\n    When the user runs \"run history\"\n    Then the command fails with error containing \"does not exist\"\n\n  # SC-RUN-010\n  Scenario: Runtime log write failures do not affect durable history\n    Given runtime log writes are failing\n    When durable history is queried via \"run history\"\n    Then durable history records are returned intact\n    And no durable history records are fabricated, removed, or reordered\n\n  # SC-RUN-011\n  Scenario: Missing run.json fails fast\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\"\n    And \"run.json\" for project \"alpha\" has been deleted\n    When the user runs \"run status\"\n    Then the command fails with error referencing \"run.json\" and \"missing\"\n\n  # SC-RUN-012\n  Scenario: Missing journal.ndjson fails fast\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\"\n    And \"journal.ndjson\" for project \"alpha\" has been deleted\n    When the user runs \"run history\"\n    Then the command fails with error referencing \"journal.ndjson\" and \"missing\"\n\n  # SC-RUN-013\n  Scenario: Orphaned payload record fails consistency check\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\"\n    And project \"alpha\" has a payload with no matching artifact\n    When the user runs \"run history\"\n    Then the command fails with error containing \"no matching artifact\"\n\n  # SC-RUN-014\n  Scenario: Run tail includes payload and artifact records in durable section\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" that has payload and artifact records\n    When the user runs \"run tail\"\n    Then the durable section includes payload and artifact records\n    And the output matches what \"run history\" would show for the same data\n\n  # SC-RUN-015\n  Scenario: Run status reports terminal completed state without active run\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" selected as active\n    And \"run.json\" for project \"alpha\" contains status \"completed\" with active_run null\n    When the user runs \"run status\"\n    Then the output includes \"completed\"\n    And the output does not include \"not started\"\n\n  # SC-RUN-016\n  Scenario: Run status reports terminal failed state without active run\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" selected as active\n    And \"run.json\" for project \"alpha\" contains status \"failed\" with active_run null\n    When the user runs \"run status\"\n    Then the output includes \"failed\"\n    And the output does not include \"not started\"\n\n  # SC-RUN-017\n  Scenario: Semantically inconsistent run.json fails fast\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\" selected as active\n    And \"run.json\" for project \"alpha\" contains status \"running\" with active_run null\n    When the user runs \"run status\"\n    Then the command fails with error referencing \"run.json\" and \"inconsistent\"\n\n  # SC-RUN-018\n  Scenario: Project delete fails for semantically inconsistent paused snapshot\n    Given an initialized workspace with project \"alpha\"\n    And \"run.json\" for project \"alpha\" contains status \"paused\" with active_run null\n    When the user runs \"project delete alpha\"\n    Then the command fails with error referencing \"run.json\" and \"inconsistent\"\n","numLines":136,"startLine":1,"totalLines":136}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_018gfxW1zqxJaAf8JPPrHUzr","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. The review feedback says:\n\n1. **Required Change**: Active-project canonical validation - commands operating on the selected project bypass `project.toml` validation. When `project.toml` is corrupt, `run status`, `run history`, and `run tail` still exit 0. The fix should validate canonical project records when resolving the active project.\n\n2. **Recommended Improvement**: Add CLI/conformance coverage for active-project corruption paths.\n\nMy plan:\n1. Update `validate_project_exists` in `workspace_governance/mod.rs` to read and parse `project.toml` (at least as valid TOML), failing fast with a `CorruptRecord` error when it's malformed.\n\n\n2. Add CLI tests for `run status`, `run history`, `run tail`, and `project show` (no ID) with corrupt `project.toml`, plus conformance scenarios for these paths.\n\nFor the implementation, I need to enhance `validate_project_exists` to not just check that the project directory and `project.toml` file exist, but also read and parse the file as valid TOML to catch corruption early. I'll parse it generically without depending on `project_run_record`'s types to keep the module boundaries clean.\n\nThe reviewer's specific issue was content corruption—garbage written to the file—so TOML parsing will catch that. I could add deeper structural validation by having the run handlers read through `FsProjectStore`, but that seems like overkill for now given the concrete repro case.\n\nActually, looking at the run handler structure more carefully, the cleanest fix is to validate the project record right after resolving the active project ID—I can add a `FsProjectStore` read there to ensure both TOML syntax and structural validity are checked before proceeding.\n\nThe tricky part is avoiding circular dependencies. Since `workspace_governance` sits upstream of `project_run_record`, I need to be careful about what I import where. Let me think through whether parsing as a raw `toml::Value` first, then as a full project record, would work without creating import cycles.\n\nActually, the reviewer's feedback is clear: the run-query path must fail if the canonical project file is corrupted. So I should add validation in the CLI handlers themselves using `FsProjectStore::read_project_record`, which gives me both syntax and structural checking. I'll also parse as `toml::Value` in `validate_project_exists` as a first line of defense. Now I need to identify which handlers need these checks—starting with `handle_status`.\n\nLooking at `handle_show`, it resolves the active project and then calls `show_project`, which internally uses `store.project_exists`. That check might already catch some issues, but I should verify whether it's sufficient or if I need explicit validation there too.\n\nFor the run commands, I'll add a direct `FsProjectStore::read_project_record` call to validate the project file. I'm also considering updating `validate_project_exists` to parse the TOML itself for extra safety—this would make `set_active_project` reject projects with corrupt `project.toml` files, which is actually the right behavior. Since the `toml` crate is already a dependency, I can use `toml::from_str::<toml::Value>()` to validate the file format. Let me proceed with these changes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":23283,"cache_read_input_tokens":51868,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":23283},"output_tokens":10,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5eb81d8b-9dcb-415b-a8cb-cb111e8f40b3","uuid":"ebe011f4-d356-4b2a-b2a2-007243745f5b"}
